WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.420 --> 00:00:04.870
PAUL: Welcome to this session
on Performance Culture.

00:00:04.870 --> 00:00:07.710
I am Paul, on the left there.

00:00:07.710 --> 00:00:10.110
I work on Google's
Developer Relations team

00:00:10.110 --> 00:00:13.790
where I spend my time looking
at performance, design, and UX

00:00:13.790 --> 00:00:16.725
and normally where the
three of those meet.

00:00:16.725 --> 00:00:18.370
LARA: And I am Lara Swanson.

00:00:18.370 --> 00:00:21.090
I work at Etsy and I'm
the Engineering Manager

00:00:21.090 --> 00:00:22.530
for the Performance team.

00:00:22.530 --> 00:00:24.220
We help all of the
feature teams who

00:00:24.220 --> 00:00:26.574
are building products or
features or experiments,

00:00:26.574 --> 00:00:28.240
make sure that whatever
they're shipping

00:00:28.240 --> 00:00:30.740
is as fast as humanly possible.

00:00:30.740 --> 00:00:34.390
PAUL: Alright so, I guess the
opening question is, why are we

00:00:34.390 --> 00:00:36.790
even talking about
performance cultures?

00:00:36.790 --> 00:00:38.570
Why does this
session even exist?

00:00:38.570 --> 00:00:40.440
And I think to
answer that we need

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:43.300
to understand a little bit
about where our industry is

00:00:43.300 --> 00:00:46.500
and what we are seeing and
where we think it's going to go.

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:47.630
And it's really about this.

00:00:47.630 --> 00:00:49.330
The multi-device web.

00:00:49.330 --> 00:00:52.900
We've seen more devices
than ever before come online

00:00:52.900 --> 00:00:55.510
and I think really the
one that stands out

00:00:55.510 --> 00:00:57.590
for me the most is this one.

00:00:57.590 --> 00:00:58.620
It's the smartphone.

00:00:58.620 --> 00:01:02.540
It represents the most
performance constrained device

00:01:02.540 --> 00:01:03.757
that we have.

00:01:03.757 --> 00:01:05.590
Whether that is in terms
of the screen size,

00:01:05.590 --> 00:01:09.230
or the GPU, the CPU, or its
connection to the network.

00:01:09.230 --> 00:01:14.000
And the thing is more and more
people are using smartphones.

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:16.740
In fact, one study suggests
that just over a third

00:01:16.740 --> 00:01:18.970
of American adults
use their smartphone

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:21.310
as the primary means of
accessing the internet.

00:01:21.310 --> 00:01:24.140
Which means for those people
their first experience

00:01:24.140 --> 00:01:26.320
of you, your site,
your brand is going

00:01:26.320 --> 00:01:27.890
to be through their smartphone.

00:01:27.890 --> 00:01:30.760
And that is something that we
need to be thinking through.

00:01:30.760 --> 00:01:34.310
In fact, it's not just in the
States it's also globally.

00:01:34.310 --> 00:01:37.560
So, here we have the percentage
of total global internet

00:01:37.560 --> 00:01:39.310
traffic according
to Stat Counter

00:01:39.310 --> 00:01:43.150
and you can see that the
trend is pretty clear upwards.

00:01:43.150 --> 00:01:46.675
And it looks I think sort
of the middle of next year,

00:01:46.675 --> 00:01:48.300
if the trend line is
correct, that well

00:01:48.300 --> 00:01:51.020
cross that 50% marker.

00:01:51.020 --> 00:01:53.690
So the thing about this is--

00:01:53.690 --> 00:01:56.940
LARA: Mobile networks can add
a tremendous amount of latency.

00:01:56.940 --> 00:01:59.535
So, before a mobile device
can transmit or receive data

00:01:59.535 --> 00:02:02.470
it has to establish a radio
channel with the network.

00:02:02.470 --> 00:02:06.470
And this can take several
seconds over a 3G connection.

00:02:06.470 --> 00:02:08.370
After the device
talks to a radio tower

00:02:08.370 --> 00:02:10.580
to negotiate when it
can transmit data,

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:13.030
the network carrier then
must transmit that data

00:02:13.030 --> 00:02:16.070
to its internal network, and
then to the public internet.

00:02:16.070 --> 00:02:17.550
So, the combination
of these steps

00:02:17.550 --> 00:02:20.970
can add up to tens of
thousands of milliseconds

00:02:20.970 --> 00:02:23.360
of extra latency.

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:25.330
So, the most
important question I

00:02:25.330 --> 00:02:27.570
hear when I say this
is, well what about 4G?

00:02:27.570 --> 00:02:29.010
4G is awesome right?

00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:30.610
Our networks are improving.

00:02:30.610 --> 00:02:34.330
But you have to remember the
new device and fast network

00:02:34.330 --> 00:02:37.090
with an excellent connection
that you have in your pocket

00:02:37.090 --> 00:02:40.580
right now is not a good
representation of what your end

00:02:40.580 --> 00:02:42.680
users are really experiencing.

00:02:42.680 --> 00:02:44.980
So, while it's true that
networks are getting better

00:02:44.980 --> 00:02:46.950
you need to remember
that your users are

00:02:46.950 --> 00:02:49.350
on a variety of connections,
with various levels

00:02:49.350 --> 00:02:52.820
of connectivity, and latency.

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:56.000
It's also important to remember
that if you're a site is slow

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:57.650
people will go elsewhere.

00:02:57.650 --> 00:03:03.390
In fact, one study suggests
that as many as 40% of people

00:03:03.390 --> 00:03:06.320
will leave a site when it
takes longer than three seconds

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:09.220
to load.

00:03:09.220 --> 00:03:10.537
So, we have some options.

00:03:10.537 --> 00:03:12.370
In the face of the stuff
that's a little bit

00:03:12.370 --> 00:03:15.676
scary what can we do about it?

00:03:15.676 --> 00:03:17.050
The first option
is to ignore it.

00:03:17.050 --> 00:03:18.970
You can certainly say,
you know what we just

00:03:18.970 --> 00:03:20.160
saw those awesome stats.

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:23.131
We say that we're
actually-- we're trying,

00:03:23.131 --> 00:03:24.755
but we don't think
it's that important.

00:03:24.755 --> 00:03:26.170
Maybe mobile isn't the future,
maybe that trend line is going

00:03:26.170 --> 00:03:28.827
to lie to us, maybe networks
will be better immediately,

00:03:28.827 --> 00:03:30.160
I don't think that this is true.

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:32.840
PAUL: No, I tend to think-- no.

00:03:32.840 --> 00:03:34.910
LARA: I think that we
can't just ignore it.

00:03:34.910 --> 00:03:35.860
PAUL: I'd like to.

00:03:35.860 --> 00:03:37.443
LARA: Yeah, it'd be
really cool, but I

00:03:37.443 --> 00:03:40.585
think the other option is
to assign performance cops.

00:03:40.585 --> 00:03:41.290
Right?

00:03:41.290 --> 00:03:43.850
Who in here would identified
as a performance cop or janitor

00:03:43.850 --> 00:03:44.675
within their organization?

00:03:44.675 --> 00:03:46.115
PAUL: Anybody ever
been one of those?

00:03:46.115 --> 00:03:47.956
LARA: Yeah, somebody who
comes in afterwards cleans up.

00:03:47.956 --> 00:03:49.039
PAUL: Look at these hands.

00:03:49.039 --> 00:03:52.670
Look at this. [DEEP VOICE]
Yes that's me, I don't know.

00:03:52.670 --> 00:03:54.430
LARA: So, performance
cops, right?

00:03:54.430 --> 00:03:57.976
We come in and we say, hey
designer, hey developer here's

00:03:57.976 --> 00:03:59.350
some better ways
you can do this.

00:03:59.350 --> 00:04:00.896
You come in cleaning
up after people,

00:04:00.896 --> 00:04:02.270
you try to make
your site better,

00:04:02.270 --> 00:04:05.430
but the responsibility
solely rests on you.

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:08.340
And this can often lead to a
tremendous amount of burnout

00:04:08.340 --> 00:04:09.816
and frankly, it's
not sustainable.

00:04:09.816 --> 00:04:11.690
There's always going to
be new people joining

00:04:11.690 --> 00:04:14.590
your organization, your site
will continue to get slower,

00:04:14.590 --> 00:04:16.310
it'll continue to
be iterated upon,

00:04:16.310 --> 00:04:18.884
the hardware age,
being a performance cop

00:04:18.884 --> 00:04:21.279
is not a sustainable
thing, so that's

00:04:21.279 --> 00:04:23.940
why we're here to talk about
building performance cultures.

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:26.676
PAUL: Wow, I wonder which one
we'll choose from that list?

00:04:26.676 --> 00:04:27.470
[LAUGH]

00:04:27.470 --> 00:04:31.890
PAUL: So, we're all set to build
a performance culture, super.

00:04:31.890 --> 00:04:33.415
But we have to ask
the question what

00:04:33.415 --> 00:04:35.540
do we even mean by a culture.

00:04:35.540 --> 00:04:38.002
Well I guess you could come
up with your own definitions

00:04:38.002 --> 00:04:39.960
goodness knows there's
probably a bunch of them

00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:41.720
that you could think
up, but for us today,

00:04:41.720 --> 00:04:44.060
at least in this conversation,
here's the things

00:04:44.060 --> 00:04:45.780
that we actually have in mind.

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:49.490
Firstly, it's a way of saying,
I belong to this group,

00:04:49.490 --> 00:04:51.660
I get them, hopefully
they get me,

00:04:51.660 --> 00:04:53.590
I understand this
particular group.

00:04:53.590 --> 00:04:56.180
So, for example being
British, I would

00:04:56.180 --> 00:04:57.535
identify with British culture.

00:04:57.535 --> 00:04:58.410
LARA: You're British?

00:04:58.410 --> 00:05:00.785
I know right it's a relief
for anybody in the room going,

00:05:00.785 --> 00:05:01.500
where is he from?

00:05:01.500 --> 00:05:03.083
His American accent
is really strange.

00:05:03.083 --> 00:05:04.499
LARA: [LAUGH]

00:05:04.499 --> 00:05:05.040
Yeah, I know.

00:05:07.990 --> 00:05:10.470
So, it's that first and
foremost is just saying,

00:05:10.470 --> 00:05:14.200
yep this is my kind of people.

00:05:14.200 --> 00:05:16.590
It's also about how
you think and how

00:05:16.590 --> 00:05:19.650
you reason and rationalize
the world around you

00:05:19.650 --> 00:05:21.150
and the kind of
social cues that you

00:05:21.150 --> 00:05:25.450
look for or the slightly strange
obsession with green liquids

00:05:25.450 --> 00:05:28.580
you may or may
not have, but it's

00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:31.130
that sense of the
world around you.

00:05:31.130 --> 00:05:33.410
It's also how you do things.

00:05:33.410 --> 00:05:35.340
Whether that's the
side of the road

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:39.670
you drive on maybe the
wrong side, the words

00:05:39.670 --> 00:05:41.815
that you use for
things or perhaps

00:05:41.815 --> 00:05:44.790
in our case how we go
about crafting the code.

00:05:44.790 --> 00:05:47.370
And then lastly, it's
how you celebrate things,

00:05:47.370 --> 00:05:49.270
the things that are
important to you,

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:50.980
the things that you
celebrate and how

00:05:50.980 --> 00:05:53.880
you go about celebrating it
is unique to your culture.

00:05:53.880 --> 00:05:56.670
And we see cultures
at the highest level

00:05:56.670 --> 00:06:00.910
internationally, nationally,
all the way down to our homes

00:06:00.910 --> 00:06:04.040
and so forth, and actually
of course, our workplaces,

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:06.290
which brings us back to that
whole performance culture

00:06:06.290 --> 00:06:07.814
thing.

00:06:07.814 --> 00:06:09.230
LARA: Yeah, we
were joking when we

00:06:09.230 --> 00:06:11.800
were talking about earlier
that performance cultures are

00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:13.650
kind of a team sport.

00:06:13.650 --> 00:06:16.520
It's important to remember
that everybody has to play.

00:06:16.520 --> 00:06:20.140
And as you say about sports
there is no "I" in performance.

00:06:20.140 --> 00:06:23.170
PAUL: That is true, but if
you're willing to look hard

00:06:23.170 --> 00:06:25.610
enough you'll find there
is "prance-for-me".

00:06:29.860 --> 00:06:31.170
You can stop the slide now.

00:06:31.170 --> 00:06:32.128
LARA: Alright, alright.

00:06:32.128 --> 00:06:33.460
So, thank you for that.

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:36.280
So, culture change is
scary and it's hard

00:06:36.280 --> 00:06:38.965
and I can understand especially
for those of us in this room,

00:06:38.965 --> 00:06:40.840
we don't know necessarily
how to approach it.

00:06:40.840 --> 00:06:44.120
How do we start to create
or enact performance culture

00:06:44.120 --> 00:06:46.466
within our environments?

00:06:46.466 --> 00:06:48.340
I'm going to go through
some real things that

00:06:48.340 --> 00:06:49.790
have been said to
me as I've gone

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:53.700
on this journey within the
organizations I've worked in.

00:06:53.700 --> 00:06:58.060
Lara, "I don't want to
think about mobile."

00:06:58.060 --> 00:06:59.032
Right.

00:06:59.032 --> 00:06:59.956
PAUL: So whiney!

00:06:59.956 --> 00:07:01.690
LARA: Yeah.

00:07:01.690 --> 00:07:04.520
"Lara, I'm a project
manager or a product manager

00:07:04.520 --> 00:07:07.490
and I've look at the deadlines,
I've got some resources

00:07:07.490 --> 00:07:10.270
and frankly building for both
desktop and mobile is going

00:07:10.270 --> 00:07:15.250
to take twice as long."
[WHISPER] It's a lie.

00:07:15.250 --> 00:07:17.800
"Lara, you at the
performance Manager,

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:20.220
don't you know
responsive web design is

00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:23.210
inherently bad for performance?"

00:07:23.210 --> 00:07:29.700
Or my personal favorite,
"everything changes too fast!"

00:07:29.700 --> 00:07:32.550
So, here's the thing we've
been through this before

00:07:32.550 --> 00:07:35.200
and when it comes
to web development

00:07:35.200 --> 00:07:38.680
we've gone through these
kinds of change the past.

00:07:38.680 --> 00:07:43.570
Who here has built sites
with tables for layout?

00:07:43.570 --> 00:07:44.150
Yes.

00:07:44.150 --> 00:07:44.934
PAUL: Yes!

00:07:44.934 --> 00:07:46.600
Look at all these guilty hands.

00:07:46.600 --> 00:07:47.400
[DEEP VOICE] I don't
do it any more.

00:07:47.400 --> 00:07:48.310
LARA: It was a pain.

00:07:48.310 --> 00:07:51.260
So, at probably every job
I worked at between 2006

00:07:51.260 --> 00:07:54.060
and 2010 I remember
these arguments,

00:07:54.060 --> 00:07:56.050
do we have to move to
a CSS based layout?

00:07:56.050 --> 00:07:57.980
In fact, we did.

00:07:57.980 --> 00:07:59.360
We did it pretty successfully.

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:01.110
This is more like what
we would use today,

00:08:01.110 --> 00:08:05.610
as is actually said to change
again with web components.

00:08:05.610 --> 00:08:08.150
Who has heard this from a very
important person, excuse me,

00:08:08.150 --> 00:08:10.537
the important part is
not above the fold.

00:08:10.537 --> 00:08:12.620
When the EP's would have
to scroll to see content.

00:08:12.620 --> 00:08:13.770
Yeah.

00:08:13.770 --> 00:08:15.510
This is again what
we're seeing today.

00:08:15.510 --> 00:08:18.530
We used to worry about
800 by 600 pixel monitors,

00:08:18.530 --> 00:08:21.770
now we're worrying about the
spectrum of screen sizes.

00:08:21.770 --> 00:08:24.380
This graphic represents
all the devices

00:08:24.380 --> 00:08:27.180
that come to ETSY.com that
have more than 1,000,000 visits

00:08:27.180 --> 00:08:28.710
per month in traffic.

00:08:28.710 --> 00:08:31.180
We're no longer seeing
just handsets and tablets

00:08:31.180 --> 00:08:35.880
and desktops we're seeing
a spectrum of screen sizes.

00:08:35.880 --> 00:08:37.370
You may also think
about how we've

00:08:37.370 --> 00:08:40.120
changed developing for
different browsers over time.

00:08:40.120 --> 00:08:42.620
I remember back in the day we
would talk about cross browser

00:08:42.620 --> 00:08:46.690
compatibility or making things
look the same across browsers.

00:08:46.690 --> 00:08:48.880
Browser hacks, prefixes,
et cetera and this

00:08:48.880 --> 00:08:50.615
is again what
we're seeing today.

00:08:50.615 --> 00:08:52.740
We have to start thinking
about mobile web browsers

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:56.660
in addition to just
our desktop clients.

00:08:56.660 --> 00:08:58.710
But this is all to say
that change is scary,

00:08:58.710 --> 00:09:01.290
but it's also constant in
our industry and it's good.

00:09:01.290 --> 00:09:03.420
This is a good part of our jobs.

00:09:03.420 --> 00:09:05.770
We've lost crazy table
layouts and now we

00:09:05.770 --> 00:09:08.480
have semantic markup and
more people than ever

00:09:08.480 --> 00:09:10.960
before can use our
sights on our apps.

00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:12.620
This is good for
us as developers

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:15.450
and it's really good for users.

00:09:15.450 --> 00:09:19.410
PAUL: So, we need to
embrace change, good, fine.

00:09:19.410 --> 00:09:21.180
So, where do we
start when we want

00:09:21.180 --> 00:09:23.250
to create one of these
performance cultures?

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:27.080
Well, the first step for us is
to actually gather some data

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:29.210
because essentially you
don't know where you're

00:09:29.210 --> 00:09:31.950
going if you don't
know where you are

00:09:31.950 --> 00:09:36.280
and you need to understand
how real people use

00:09:36.280 --> 00:09:38.330
your site, like what
devices are they on?

00:09:38.330 --> 00:09:39.810
Where are they in the world?

00:09:39.810 --> 00:09:43.175
What journey did they
take through your site?

00:09:43.175 --> 00:09:45.050
Which pages did they
arrive on and which ones

00:09:45.050 --> 00:09:45.799
did they leave on?

00:09:45.799 --> 00:09:48.620
You need to understand
your own situation

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:50.170
and if you don't
know today you can't

00:09:50.170 --> 00:09:52.770
start telling that story
to the people around you

00:09:52.770 --> 00:09:55.540
and get them on board to
build this culture with you.

00:09:55.540 --> 00:09:57.430
So, the immediate thing
that springs to mind

00:09:57.430 --> 00:09:59.430
is just going and have a
look at your analytics.

00:09:59.430 --> 00:10:00.580
Go and look at Google Analytics.

00:10:00.580 --> 00:10:01.954
Figure out what
it's telling you.

00:10:01.954 --> 00:10:03.650
Spend a bit of
time, make reports,

00:10:03.650 --> 00:10:06.862
and start to get that
sense of where you're at.

00:10:06.862 --> 00:10:08.570
The next thing you
want to do is actually

00:10:08.570 --> 00:10:10.209
look at you load stats.

00:10:10.209 --> 00:10:11.750
So, how long does
it take to load it?

00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:15.570
How long does it feel like
it takes to load your site?

00:10:15.570 --> 00:10:19.487
Again this is coming down to
the data that you can share,

00:10:19.487 --> 00:10:21.070
but it's also in
this case coming down

00:10:21.070 --> 00:10:22.930
to a little bit of
empathy as well.

00:10:22.930 --> 00:10:25.700
How does it actually feel to
be one of those people that's

00:10:25.700 --> 00:10:27.480
using your site on
a day to day basis

00:10:27.480 --> 00:10:29.010
from somewhere
else in the world.

00:10:29.010 --> 00:10:31.940
And for that we can
turn to Web Page Test

00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:35.730
and you can ask it to load your
site from a range of locations,

00:10:35.730 --> 00:10:37.860
a bunch of devices, and
different connection types.

00:10:37.860 --> 00:10:40.440
And it is going to give you a
load of really useful, really

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:41.270
amazing data.

00:10:41.270 --> 00:10:43.610
And one feature I
particularly like

00:10:43.610 --> 00:10:46.250
is the ability to compare pages,
so you could take for example

00:10:46.250 --> 00:10:48.440
your own site and
oh, I don't know,

00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:51.709
the site of your co-presenter
and see who's fastest.

00:10:51.709 --> 00:10:52.500
LARA: Not cool bro.

00:10:52.500 --> 00:10:53.950
PAUL: Oh yeah.

00:10:53.950 --> 00:10:56.590
I actually did
that, as you can see

00:10:56.590 --> 00:10:58.977
and depressingly it's a draw.

