00:21:41.310 --> 00:21:42.980
And these tools can
even report back

00:21:42.980 --> 00:21:45.840
to dashboards, which is
my next recommendation.

00:21:45.840 --> 00:21:48.550
So, at Etsy we look at something
like this every time we deploy

00:21:48.550 --> 00:21:51.020
code, which happens
upwards of 50 times a day.

00:21:51.020 --> 00:21:52.690
When someone deploys
something new

00:21:52.690 --> 00:21:54.500
they'll go over to
a dashboard and say,

00:21:54.500 --> 00:21:56.184
how did this impact performance?

00:21:56.184 --> 00:21:58.350
It's really important that
as people are continually

00:21:58.350 --> 00:22:00.770
pushing out new work
they can see immediately

00:22:00.770 --> 00:22:03.320
how their stuff has affected it.

00:22:03.320 --> 00:22:05.770
But also at Etsy we
have this tool bar

00:22:05.770 --> 00:22:08.310
that sits at the top of
every page of etsy.com

00:22:08.310 --> 00:22:10.666
if you logged in as
an Etsy employee.

00:22:10.666 --> 00:22:12.040
And in this we've
got information

00:22:12.040 --> 00:22:13.690
about visitor traffic
and experiments,

00:22:13.690 --> 00:22:15.990
but we also have
performance data.

00:22:15.990 --> 00:22:17.780
So, we surface the
timing's for people

00:22:17.780 --> 00:22:20.790
as they're developing
in developing, staging,

00:22:20.790 --> 00:22:22.380
and production environments.

00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:23.842
And we also have
a clear baseline

00:22:23.842 --> 00:22:24.800
for what is acceptable.

00:22:24.800 --> 00:22:26.800
We'll let you know
if you're violating

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:30.200
one of our performance
service level agreements.

00:22:30.200 --> 00:22:32.140
By surfacing your
team's performance data

00:22:32.140 --> 00:22:34.640
during the workflow it'll
help improve their work,

00:22:34.640 --> 00:22:36.409
it'll become baked
into their workflow.

00:22:36.409 --> 00:22:38.200
They'll start to care
about it because they

00:22:38.200 --> 00:22:40.050
can see how their work
directly impacts it

00:22:40.050 --> 00:22:42.990
as they're designing
and developing.

00:22:42.990 --> 00:22:45.080
And this brings me
to our last point.

00:22:45.080 --> 00:22:46.970
This stuff is going to
make people so excited

00:22:46.970 --> 00:22:48.428
and people are
going to ship things

00:22:48.428 --> 00:22:50.060
that are improvements
to your site.

00:22:50.060 --> 00:22:52.000
You should be
celebrating everything.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:22:53.705
Again, I'm all about
the excitement.

00:22:53.705 --> 00:22:56.080
I'm all about getting people
pumped up about performance.

00:22:56.080 --> 00:22:57.455
PAUL: Prepping
the talk with Lara

00:22:57.455 --> 00:22:59.300
was like an object
lesson in excitement.

00:22:59.300 --> 00:23:00.250
LARA: Nice.

00:23:00.250 --> 00:23:03.890
So, for me, this is actually
the most important part.

00:23:03.890 --> 00:23:05.950
Back in the day
in August of 2011

00:23:05.950 --> 00:23:08.010
the man behind the
sunglasses, Seth Walker,

00:23:08.010 --> 00:23:11.000
published Etsy's first
performance report.

00:23:11.000 --> 00:23:15.860
He published it on Etsy's news
blog, so it's super public.

00:23:15.860 --> 00:23:18.430
He chose a bunch of baseline
business metrics or page load

00:23:18.430 --> 00:23:20.420
time metrics,
rather and he showed

00:23:20.420 --> 00:23:23.330
how long are our major
pages were taking to load

00:23:23.330 --> 00:23:25.952
and you can see there's a huge
outlier here, the homepage.

00:23:25.952 --> 00:23:27.910
It was embarrassing, but
he published it anyway

00:23:27.910 --> 00:23:30.160
because this stuff
isn't a secret.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:33.470
What's amazing about this
is that developers teamed up

00:23:33.470 --> 00:23:34.246
to fix this.

00:23:34.246 --> 00:23:35.620
As soon as we
publish it, as soon

00:23:35.620 --> 00:23:38.470
as Seth put that into the world
people got excited about it

00:23:38.470 --> 00:23:40.890
and they wanted to help
and they want to fix it.

00:23:40.890 --> 00:23:43.590
And by the next time we
published reports, which

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:46.860
was in November of 2011
there was a huge improvement.

00:23:46.860 --> 00:23:49.255
Not only did the home
page significantly improve

00:23:49.255 --> 00:23:50.520
in page load time.

00:23:50.520 --> 00:23:53.990
It was the fastest
one on this list.

00:23:53.990 --> 00:23:55.675
So, you should be
sharing your findings.

00:23:55.675 --> 00:23:57.050
Make sure that
you're celebrating

00:23:57.050 --> 00:23:59.990
externally the stuff that you're
doing to help improve things

00:23:59.990 --> 00:24:02.430
along the way, but
also as Paul mentioned

00:24:02.430 --> 00:24:04.801
it's important to do
this internally as well.

00:24:04.801 --> 00:24:06.550
This is an example
dashboard that we have,

00:24:06.550 --> 00:24:08.020
the Performance
Hero a dashboard,

00:24:08.020 --> 00:24:10.670
in which we celebrate
engineers and designers who

00:24:10.670 --> 00:24:13.200
make huge improvements
to Etsy's page load time

00:24:13.200 --> 00:24:15.560
and they're not on
the performance team.

00:24:15.560 --> 00:24:18.460
In this case Chris Fairbanks,
who's on the checkout team,

00:24:18.460 --> 00:24:20.680
eliminated a ton
of duplicate code

00:24:20.680 --> 00:24:22.139
and had what we
call a Baumgartner.

00:24:22.139 --> 00:24:24.429
Remember that guy who jumped
out of the hot air balloon

00:24:24.429 --> 00:24:25.500
and landed on earth?

00:24:25.500 --> 00:24:27.496
Yeah so every time we
have a graph like this--

00:24:27.496 --> 00:24:28.290
PAUL: It wasn't a
dance move, right?

00:24:28.290 --> 00:24:30.225
LARA: It wasn't-- no, it wasn't
a dance move it was a plummet

00:24:30.225 --> 00:24:31.072
to earth.

00:24:31.072 --> 00:24:33.030
Every time we have one
of these, a Baumgartner,

00:24:33.030 --> 00:24:34.430
we celebrate this internally.

00:24:34.430 --> 00:24:36.100
We put this up on
a dashboard and we

00:24:36.100 --> 00:24:38.650
have that little printout
sign, and we hang out with them

00:24:38.650 --> 00:24:39.608
and we're like, thanks.

00:24:39.608 --> 00:24:40.280
Thanks buddy.

00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:42.196
And we want to celebrate
the things internally

00:24:42.196 --> 00:24:46.130
lots of high fives, lots
of doughnuts, lots of cake.

00:24:46.130 --> 00:24:48.034
You should be rewarding
your innovators.

00:24:48.034 --> 00:24:49.950
It's not just about
coming down with a hammer.

00:24:49.950 --> 00:24:51.694
It's not about being
a cop or a janitor.

00:24:51.694 --> 00:24:54.360
This is really about celebrating
improvements and getting people

00:24:54.360 --> 00:24:57.510
excited and invested
in their performance.

00:24:57.510 --> 00:24:59.710
Celebrating wins will
motivate your team

00:24:59.710 --> 00:25:02.280
to be performance champions.

00:25:02.280 --> 00:25:05.622
So, to summarize
gather the data.

00:25:05.622 --> 00:25:07.080
You want to make
sure that you have

00:25:07.080 --> 00:25:10.410
a baseline of understanding
how your users feel.

00:25:10.410 --> 00:25:13.250
Again, this is all about
understanding the overall user

00:25:13.250 --> 00:25:13.800
experience.

00:25:13.800 --> 00:25:17.230
It's the aesthetics and
it's page load time.

00:25:17.230 --> 00:25:20.340
You then want to share all
that stuff with your VIP's.

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:23.260
Get them to understand what your
users are really experiencing.

00:25:23.260 --> 00:25:25.996
Get them to understand what it's
like on mobile and globally.

00:25:25.996 --> 00:25:28.620
Get them to understand also how
this stuff impacts the business

00:25:28.620 --> 00:25:32.560
metrics, run some experiments
and share that data with them.

00:25:32.560 --> 00:25:34.420
Once you get a very
important person to say,

00:25:34.420 --> 00:25:36.961
this is important or just a few
find that it's awesome enough

00:25:36.961 --> 00:25:38.990
to say this is important,
educate your team.

00:25:38.990 --> 00:25:41.270
Do those brown bags
and lunch and learns.

00:25:41.270 --> 00:25:43.728
Make sure that your surfacing
that data in their daily work

00:25:43.728 --> 00:25:44.670
flows.

00:25:44.670 --> 00:25:50.300
Make sure also-- your
celebrating things.

00:25:50.300 --> 00:25:51.550
Again this is a journey right?

00:25:51.550 --> 00:25:53.210
You may be at any
step in this process

00:25:53.210 --> 00:25:55.459
and you might have to start
again gathering more data,

00:25:55.459 --> 00:25:58.065
getting more VIP buy in,
educating the team again.

00:25:58.065 --> 00:25:59.741
New designers and
developers will join

00:25:59.741 --> 00:26:01.990
and you'll have to do more
brown bag lunch and learns.

00:26:01.990 --> 00:26:03.360
New technologies will
emerge and you'll

00:26:03.360 --> 00:26:05.910
want to share that data and
that new information with them.

00:26:05.910 --> 00:26:08.440
You'll find new wins and you
want to celebrate that stuff.

00:26:08.440 --> 00:26:12.846
This is a continual journey and
continually positive process.

00:26:12.846 --> 00:26:13.346
PAUL: OK.

00:26:13.346 --> 00:26:15.710
So, as we said at
the start we're

00:26:15.710 --> 00:26:17.910
in this period of
dramatic change

00:26:17.910 --> 00:26:22.760
where we're seeing mobile
traffic go, whoosh straight up,

00:26:22.760 --> 00:26:28.190
and we're facing this
world where essentially we

00:26:28.190 --> 00:26:30.920
need to deal with these
performance constrained devices

00:26:30.920 --> 00:26:33.220
like building for this
tomorrow that we're looking

00:26:33.220 --> 00:26:35.800
at involves facing
that fight and saying

00:26:35.800 --> 00:26:38.340
you know what most of the
devices that people are going

00:26:38.340 --> 00:26:41.570
to be using are not desktop,
they are not powerful devices.

00:26:41.570 --> 00:26:45.280
The thing is it's not really
tomorrow it's kind of now.

00:26:45.280 --> 00:26:48.200
And that's the thing about
dealing with performance

00:26:48.200 --> 00:26:50.750
is it really starts and it
can and should start today,

00:26:50.750 --> 00:26:53.690
but the only way you're
going to get to that point

00:26:53.690 --> 00:26:58.490
is if absolutely everybody in
your organization from the top

00:26:58.490 --> 00:27:02.291
to the bottom cares deeply about
performance and its impact.

00:27:02.291 --> 00:27:03.790
And the only way
you're going to get

00:27:03.790 --> 00:27:08.300
there is if you start
building performance cultures.

00:27:08.300 --> 00:27:08.800
Thank you.

